label.value: Helper T-Lymphocytes to Cytotoxic T-Lymphocytes Ratio Measurement

value.value: A relative measurement (ratio) of the helper T-lymphocytes to cytotoxic T-lymphocytes present in a sample. The measurement may be expressed as a ratio or percentage.

label.value: Natural Killer Cells to Leukocytes Ratio Measurement

value.value: The determination of the ratio of the natural killer cells to leukocytes present in a sample. The measurement may be expressed as a ratio or percentage.
The determination of B-lymphocytes B1 in a biospecimen.
A measurement of a subpopulation of B-lymphocytes B1 in a biospecimen.
A subdiscipline of immunology with a focus on the nervous system and its interactions with the immune system.
An indication as to whether the subject received a treatment dosage and/or regimen that is expected to be therapeutic, based on standards of care or per protocol.
The longest diameter of the lesion that has been determined to be the primary lesion.
The number of fistulas observed.
The number of abscesses observed.
A classification based on the anatomical location(s) of the fistula.
The anatomical location of the lesion that has been determined to be the primary lesion.
An indication as to whether a biopsy specimen was collected.
The total number of biopsy specimens collected.
A description of the appearance of the anatomical site from which a biopsy specimen has been collected.
A subject domain utilized for the submission of information encompassing and representing data, vocabulary or records related to cell phenotype findings.
Model for high performance computing in which a problem is solved by multiple processors working cooperatively and simultaneously.
A subject domain utilized for the submission of information encompassing and representing data, vocabulary or records related to genomics findings.
A dataset used to represent relationships between specimens. (CDISC)

label.value: Study Data Technical Conformance Guide v4.6

value.value: Version 4.6 of the FDA Study Data Technical Conformance Guide.

label.value: Study Data Technical Conformance Guide v4.7

value.value: Version 4.7 of the FDA Study Data Technical Conformance Guide.

label.value: Transcript Fragment Count per Million Formula

value.value: A formula that normalizes transcript fragment counts based on the total number of transcript fragments that are sequenced. CPM equals the number of reads divided by the number of sequenced transcript fragments, and multiplied by 1,000,000.

A formula that calculates the number of fragments per million fragments sampled (calculated by dividing the fragment counts by a per million scaling factor, which is derived by taking the total fragments in the sample and dividing by 1,000,000) divided by the length of the gene, in kilobases. Fragments are represented by either paired or single end reads.

A formula that calculates the number of reads per million fragments sampled (calculated by dividing the fragment counts by a per million scaling factor, which is derived by taking the total fragments in the sample and dividing by 1,000,000) divided by the length of the gene, in kilobases. Fragments are represented by single end reads.

A formula that identifies the transcripts per kilobase (RPK, derived by dividing the read counts by the length of each gene, in kilobases) divided by a per million scaling factor (which is the count of RPK values in a sample divided by 1,000,000).
A formula that compares gene expression by calculating the log2 fold difference between two gene expression intensities, or 2^(Value 2 Intensity - Value 1 Intensity).
A unique pattern of gene expression of one to many combinations of genes that is associated with type 1 interferon activity.
A point mutation occurring within the protein-coding region of a gene, and which codes for a different amino acid than expected.
An assessment of the variability in the number of replicas of a gene within the genome.
An assessment of the variability in a nucleotide found within a specified position of the genome, when compared to a reference nucleotide.
An assessment of the variability in length of microsatellite sequences.
An assessment of the unique pattern of gene expression of one to many genes associated with a normal or abnormal biological process.
An assessment of the variability in a short sequence of nucleotides (generally defined as 50 base pairs or less), when compared to a reference sequence.
A quantitative or qualitative assessment of the number of genomic alterations found in genetic material from tumor cells, when compared to a reference sequence.
The number of replicas of a particular gene sequence in a genome.
An interpretive summary of the number of replicas of a gene or gene segment within a genome, as compared to a reference or assumed state.
An indication as to whether a genetic sequence is transcribed into RNA.
An interpretive summary of the pattern of genetic transcription.

A relatively common point mutation in which a purine is exchanged for a nonidentical purine or a pyrimidine is exchanged for a nonidentical pyrimidine. Base mispairing and mutagenic chemicals including nitrous acid and 5-bromo-2-deoxyuridine can result in transitions.
The number or amount of raw fragments of genetic material that were analyzed.
An amount that is adjusted to a reference standard.
A ranking of what percent of the reference population the individual would equal or exceed.
An extrapolation of the modification of an amino acid based on sequence analysis of a genetic variation.
An extrapolation of the modification of a coding sequence based on sequence analysis of a genetic variation.
A categorization of the phenotypic consequence of the genetic variation.
The number of times a particular variant within a locus (site, nucleotide, amplicon, region) was sequenced.

label.value: Variant Read Depth to Read Depth

value.value: A relative measurement (ratio or percentage) of the variant mapped reads to total mapped reads.
The number of affected exons as compared to the reference sequence.
A relative measurement (ratio) of the number of altered copies in the sample to the number of copies in the reference sequence.
A relatively less common point mutation in which a purine is exchanged for a pyrimidine or a pyrimidine is exchanged for a purine.
